1
00:02:09,496 --> 00:02:11,396
You coming or not?

2
00:03:49,267 --> 00:03:52,703
-All right, I'll get her to you right away.
-Appreciate it.

3
00:03:53,906 --> 00:03:54,930
-Hi.
-Hi.

4
00:03:55,174 --> 00:03:59,406
Dr. Klyczynski to ER, stat.
Dr. Klyczynski to ER, stat.

5
00:03:59,645 --> 00:04:02,944
-Hi, excuse me.
-Yeah, just a minute, okay?

6
00:04:04,216 --> 00:04:07,674
-Fill this out for me and wait over there.
-No, I'm... I'm Dr. Forster.

7
00:04:07,886 --> 00:04:09,217
I was told to report here.

8
00:04:09,388 --> 00:04:12,846
You'll be covering 22 patients
on rounds today, this floor and the next.

9
00:04:13,058 --> 00:04:14,685
-Twenty-two?
-Quiet morning.

10
00:04:14,893 --> 00:04:17,761
If you get into trouble, beep me,
but don't make it a habit.

11
00:04:17,964 --> 00:04:20,455
The med students
will help you out with scutwork.

12
00:04:20,667 --> 00:04:23,397
What's he doing here?
I ordered an MRI, stat.

13
00:04:23,603 --> 00:04:27,164
-Transport said about four hours.
-He could be dead in four hours.

14
00:04:27,374 --> 00:04:29,569
Never mind. Dr. Forster, MRI.

15
00:04:29,743 --> 00:04:31,802
-A right, two lefts, elevator to two.
-Okay.

16
00:04:32,045 --> 00:04:34,445
Follow the signs.
Hustle back here for rounds.

17
00:04:35,415 --> 00:04:37,110
Dr. Kly...

18
00:04:38,752 --> 00:04:42,211
-Are you taking me somewhere?
-I certainly hope so, sir.

19
00:04:42,423 --> 00:04:45,187
-How are you feeling today?
-Am...? Am I gonna make it?

20
00:04:45,993 --> 00:04:48,086
Yes. Absolutely.

21
00:04:52,299 --> 00:04:54,199
Alex!

22
00:04:54,402 --> 00:04:58,736
I made my famous spinach pie.
The trailer's nice and toasty.

23
00:04:58,939 --> 00:05:00,804
I can't.

24
00:05:03,311 --> 00:05:07,270
Look, it's really cold out here.
Don't get sick on me or anything.

25
00:05:07,482 --> 00:05:09,973
I never get sick.

26
00:05:10,719 --> 00:05:14,917
So I heard you bought a house,
and apparently I'm the last one to know.

27
00:05:15,123 --> 00:05:16,522
I thought I mentioned that.

28
00:05:16,758 --> 00:05:18,453
Wait.

29
00:05:19,127 --> 00:05:20,424
Where?

30
00:05:20,629 --> 00:05:22,927
Outside of town.
Up the shore a little bit.

31
00:05:23,131 --> 00:05:24,826
Up the shore? There's no houses...

32
00:05:25,033 --> 00:05:28,970
Oh, God. You don't mean that thing
with the stilts and the...?

33
00:05:31,607 --> 00:05:34,940
-You all right?
-Yeah. Are you crazy?

34
00:05:36,279 --> 00:05:38,975
Why would you take that house, Alex?

35
00:05:39,182 --> 00:05:41,844
It's made of glass. There's no privacy.

36
00:05:42,051 --> 00:05:43,712
Mona?

37
00:05:44,153 --> 00:05:46,451
Get yourself some boots.

38
00:05:49,258 --> 00:05:51,454
Hey, Gonzalez!

39
00:05:56,266 --> 00:05:58,200
-Four-thirty.
-You lost?

40
00:05:58,402 --> 00:06:01,462
-Yeah.
-Takes a while to get your bearings.

41
00:06:01,672 --> 00:06:04,800
-I'm Madhvi.
-Kate Forster. Hi.

42
00:06:05,008 --> 00:06:08,409
Oh, wrong floor.
Where'd you do your residency?

43
00:06:08,645 --> 00:06:11,409
Just a little community hospital
up on the North Shore.

44
00:06:32,170 --> 00:06:35,606
Dear new tenant,
welcome to your new home.

45
00:06:35,841 --> 00:06:37,570
As the previous tenant, let me say...

46
00:06:37,810 --> 00:06:40,745
...I hope you'll like living here
as much as I did.

47
00:06:40,946 --> 00:06:44,040
I filed the change of address
with the post office...

48
00:06:44,250 --> 00:06:46,582
...but you know
what a crapshoot that can be.

49
00:06:46,819 --> 00:06:50,448
So if anything slips through, would you
do me a favor and forward my mail?

50
00:06:50,689 --> 00:06:54,352
I'd appreciate it.
My new address is below.

51
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:58,394
Thanks in advance. P. S:

52
00:06:58,597 --> 00:07:03,092
"Sorry about the paw prints by the front
door. They were there when I moved in.

53
00:07:03,570 --> 00:07:06,596
Same with the box in the attic."

54
00:07:08,441 --> 00:07:12,707
Paw prints?
What the hell is she talking about?

55
00:07:26,794 --> 00:07:30,230
Hey, baby girl. Hi. Hi. Hey.

56
00:07:41,375 --> 00:07:43,468
Fix the light.

57
00:07:44,478 --> 00:07:46,606
Get dog food, huh?

58
00:07:47,649 --> 00:07:49,583
Get human food.

59
00:08:17,947 --> 00:08:21,144
Hey. Hey.

60
00:08:26,022 --> 00:08:28,183
Hey, come here.

61
00:08:37,301 --> 00:08:41,328
Sixty degrees on Valentine's Day.
Can't be Chicago.

62
00:08:41,538 --> 00:08:43,904
The TV says it's global warming.

63
00:08:44,074 --> 00:08:47,874
The icebergs start melting,
water covers the Earth.

64
00:08:48,078 --> 00:08:50,740
Thank God we won't live to see it.

65
00:08:52,149 --> 00:08:53,582
What's this?

66
00:08:54,385 --> 00:08:56,354
That's nothing.
It's one of your father's.

67
00:08:56,554 --> 00:08:59,990
-Dostoyevsky?
-Oh, yeah.

68
00:09:00,325 --> 00:09:06,662
It's about a guy who breaks the neck
of a poor woman with an axe...

69
00:09:06,865 --> 00:09:10,665
...and, so far, keeps wandering
around regretting it.

70
00:09:14,005 --> 00:09:15,472
This is good.

71
00:09:15,674 --> 00:09:19,076
-Oh, yeah?
-Yeah. It's really good.

72
00:09:20,279 --> 00:09:21,268
I'll meet you there.

73
00:09:21,514 --> 00:09:22,879
What are you thinking?

74
00:09:23,382 --> 00:09:24,781
My folks are coming into town.

75
00:09:25,017 --> 00:09:26,678
Nothing.

76
00:09:26,886 --> 00:09:31,118
When your father passed away,
it was hard. It still is hard.

77
00:09:31,290 --> 00:09:36,227
Holding his books,
I feel like he's with me somehow.

78
00:09:36,429 --> 00:09:39,193
Knowing that he was once
on the same pages...

79
00:09:39,398 --> 00:09:41,560
...reading the same words.

80
00:09:46,807 --> 00:09:50,402
Oh, my God!
Somebody call an ambulance!

81
00:09:51,111 --> 00:09:52,772
We need an ambulance at Daley Plaza.

82
00:09:53,013 --> 00:09:55,948
A man has been struck by a bus.
Get an EMT crew here. Sir...

83
00:09:56,149 --> 00:09:58,014
Get out the street.
Get on the sidewalk.

84
00:09:58,218 --> 00:10:00,015
-On the sidewalk. Off the street.
-Sir?

85
00:10:00,220 --> 00:10:02,745
Get on the sidewalk!
Get on the sidewalk!

86
00:10:02,923 --> 00:10:06,223
I'd like to get the foundation
on number 17 dug today.

87
00:10:06,828 --> 00:10:09,592
Look, I know you're
kind of new around here, kid.

88
00:10:09,797 --> 00:10:11,424
What?

89
00:10:11,632 --> 00:10:14,760
I can't get to 17 until
at least next week.

90
00:10:14,969 --> 00:10:17,961
Come on, Mulhern.
That's bullshit and you know it.

91
00:10:18,172 --> 00:10:20,470
Take Clemens and Rodriguez
off of roofing.

92
00:10:20,675 --> 00:10:23,337
Jorge can run the backhoe
they're not using on 14...

93
00:10:23,578 --> 00:10:25,739
...and grab four or five
of those other guys...

94
00:10:25,947 --> 00:10:28,246
...who are doing nothing
on seven and 10.

95
00:10:28,450 --> 00:10:32,045
Paulie, Carlos, Frank, Danny,
and what's-his-name, the tall guy?

96
00:10:32,254 --> 00:10:34,745
-Rafael.
-Rafael.

97
00:10:34,957 --> 00:10:37,755
-Let's go.
-Okay.

98
00:10:37,960 --> 00:10:39,484
-Ready?
-Yeah.

99
00:10:39,695 --> 00:10:42,027
-Well, I need it to 10 and 11.
-Hey!

100
00:10:45,634 --> 00:10:48,501
Housekeeping ER
to the Suture Room, please.

101
00:10:48,704 --> 00:10:52,197
Housekeeping ER to the Suture Room.

102
00:10:55,145 --> 00:10:57,807
-Hey.
-Hi.

103
00:10:58,014 --> 00:11:00,847
I heard about Daley Plaza.

104
00:11:01,718 --> 00:11:04,380
EMT said you fought hard for the guy.

105
00:11:04,854 --> 00:11:07,789
Yeah. Really knocked myself out.

106
00:11:08,458 --> 00:11:12,519
Kate, I'm going to tell you
what I tell every young doctor.

107
00:11:12,729 --> 00:11:15,722
Hopefully, you'll be the first to listen.

108
00:11:16,467 --> 00:11:21,632
On your day off, get as far away
from this place as you can.

109
00:11:21,839 --> 00:11:27,141
Go someplace where you feel
most like yourself.

110
00:12:22,034 --> 00:12:24,162
Dear Ms. Forster:

111
00:12:24,371 --> 00:12:25,702
I got your note...

112
00:12:25,906 --> 00:12:29,171
...and I'm afraid there must be
some kind of misunderstanding.

113
00:12:29,376 --> 00:12:33,312
As far as I know, the lake house
has been empty for several years.

114
00:12:33,547 --> 00:12:37,074
Maybe your note was intended for
the Sandburg house down the shore...

115
00:12:37,284 --> 00:12:40,776
"...since no one has lived
in this house for years.

116
00:12:41,788 --> 00:12:44,916
But I'm curious about the paw prints."

117
00:12:50,765 --> 00:12:53,893
Dear Mr. Wyler, I'm very familiar
with the Sandburg cottage...

118
00:12:54,102 --> 00:12:56,627
...and I can guarantee
I never lived there.

119
00:12:56,838 --> 00:13:00,604
I'm old-fashioned, but I don't think a
cottage should be over 6000 square feet.

120
00:13:00,808 --> 00:13:02,776
So let me try again.

121
00:13:02,977 --> 00:13:06,140
I used to live at the lake house,
then I moved.

122
00:13:06,347 --> 00:13:09,977
Now I live at 1620 North Racine
in Chicago.

123
00:13:10,219 --> 00:13:13,245
I'd appreciate it if you would
forward my mail if you get any.

124
00:13:13,455 --> 00:13:17,221
Oh, by the way, it's 2006.

125
00:13:17,426 --> 00:13:20,020
Has been all year, ask anyone.

126
00:13:20,262 --> 00:13:22,730
2006?

127
00:13:23,299 --> 00:13:25,631
What does she mean, 2006?

128
00:13:26,302 --> 00:13:28,270
God.

129
00:13:28,537 --> 00:13:29,526
Oh, God.

130
00:13:32,676 --> 00:13:34,837
-Good morning, Mr. Wyler.
-Morning, Mr. Wyler.

131
00:13:35,045 --> 00:13:36,535
-Morning, sir.
-Morning, morning.

132
00:13:36,780 --> 00:13:38,543
Hello, Mr. Wyler.

133
00:13:39,049 --> 00:13:41,017
Mr. Wyler.

134
00:13:41,818 --> 00:13:43,683
Sir.

135
00:13:45,956 --> 00:13:49,119
Well, obviously,
I derived my inspiration...

136
00:13:49,326 --> 00:13:52,557
...for the metaphor
of the fugue, the loop...

137
00:13:54,397 --> 00:13:56,059
Yeah.

138
00:14:15,886 --> 00:14:19,186
-Two hours of that shit. You kidding me?
-What are you talking about?

139
00:14:19,391 --> 00:14:23,919
-He didn't say a word.
-Sadistic, bitter, bitter old man.

140
00:14:24,162 --> 00:14:27,097
I think you're being
a little overdramatic.

141
00:14:30,936 --> 00:14:32,733
Where are you going?

142
00:14:41,546 --> 00:14:43,879
Man, I love that place.

143
00:15:05,239 --> 00:15:08,072
I can't believe that thing's
still running.

144
00:15:11,078 --> 00:15:12,705
Yep.

145
00:15:14,048 --> 00:15:15,447
You look like shit.

146
00:15:16,283 --> 00:15:18,080
I missed you too.

147
00:15:36,905 --> 00:15:39,135
Hey, forget about him.

148
00:15:43,611 --> 00:15:45,636
-Condos.
-Riviera Estates.

149
00:15:45,880 --> 00:15:47,643
-You're joking.
-I don't believe this.

150
00:15:47,882 --> 00:15:49,679
I come back after four years...

151
00:15:49,918 --> 00:15:51,784
...and I get this in front of me.
-What?

152
00:15:51,987 --> 00:15:54,114
My brother thinking
he's Frank Lloyd Whatever.

153
00:15:54,323 --> 00:15:56,291
-Oh, come on.
-Dad keeps you hostage...

154
00:15:56,492 --> 00:15:59,188
...in that little
mythmaking factory of his...

155
00:15:59,428 --> 00:16:02,761
...while you haven't built so much as
a phone booth or a hamster cage.

156
00:16:02,932 --> 00:16:04,627
That's funny you say that, actually.

157
00:16:04,834 --> 00:16:07,894
I have a hamster cage in mind.
A development of them, actually.

158
00:16:08,104 --> 00:16:11,267
Prefab, no foundations.
What do you think about that?

159
00:16:11,474 --> 00:16:14,672
See, that's what I'm talking about.
You have vision.

160
00:16:15,779 --> 00:16:17,542
Speaking of which...

161
00:16:17,781 --> 00:16:21,046
...l'd like you to know
I bought a house.

162
00:16:21,218 --> 00:16:23,277
-Where?
-On the lake.

163
00:16:23,687 --> 00:16:25,655
A lake house.
So you are making some money.

164
00:16:25,822 --> 00:16:28,313
Well, it's a dump.
Been abandoned for years, but...

165
00:16:28,525 --> 00:16:30,789
So you got an abandoned,
haunted lake hou...

166
00:16:30,994 --> 00:16:32,552
That's as good a reason as any...

167
00:16:32,796 --> 00:16:35,560
...for selling out and joining
the flabby-developers' guild.

168
00:16:35,799 --> 00:16:39,167
-How about this? I even got a dog.
-You got a dog?

169
00:16:40,371 --> 00:16:45,138
He just showed up at the house
from out of nowhere.

170
00:16:57,188 --> 00:16:59,884
-What are we doing here?
-I have to deliver a letter.

171
00:17:00,091 --> 00:17:04,529
It should be here.
1620 North Racine.

172
00:17:07,866 --> 00:17:09,527
But...

173
00:17:10,869 --> 00:17:12,097
...there's nothing here.

174
00:17:14,273 --> 00:17:17,504
Are we meeting someone?
Does somebody live here? What?

175
00:17:17,910 --> 00:17:19,605
Yeah.

176
00:17:19,845 --> 00:17:22,040
I thought so.

177
00:17:22,447 --> 00:17:23,675
Should we ring the bell?

178
00:17:42,635 --> 00:17:44,296
Dear Ms. Forster:

179
00:17:44,537 --> 00:17:48,235
I went to 1620 North Racine,
and it's not there.

180
00:17:48,642 --> 00:17:50,633
It's just a construction site.

181
00:17:50,878 --> 00:17:54,939
From the pictures it looks nice,
but not for another 18 months.

182
00:17:55,149 --> 00:17:57,117
What am I missing here?

183
00:17:57,318 --> 00:18:00,810
Maybe you got the address wrong,
because you got the date wrong too.

184
00:18:01,055 --> 00:18:03,888
You really wanna play this game.

185
00:18:04,725 --> 00:18:10,027
If you are truly in the year 2004...

186
00:18:10,732 --> 00:18:13,030
...then...

187
00:18:15,303 --> 00:18:17,396
...be forewarned.

188
00:18:19,140 --> 00:18:23,668
Remember that day?
You were not happy. Remember that?

189
00:18:24,846 --> 00:18:26,074
I know.

190
00:18:26,681 --> 00:18:29,616
Okay, my mystery correspondent,
I get it.

191
00:18:29,818 --> 00:18:33,185
Just in case you really are
where and when you think you are...

192
00:18:33,421 --> 00:18:34,980
...you'll need this.

193
00:18:35,191 --> 00:18:38,490
There was a freak late snow that spring
and everyone got sick.

194
00:18:38,694 --> 00:18:43,324
So plenty of rest, lots of fluids.
Doctor's orders.

195
00:18:43,566 --> 00:18:46,433
Snow. Right.

196
00:18:51,107 --> 00:18:54,076
Yeah, come to papa.

197
00:20:30,378 --> 00:20:32,107
Jackie.

198
00:20:33,280 --> 00:20:35,043
Jack.

199
00:20:35,449 --> 00:20:38,577
Jack, come on. Come on, girl.
Come on, come on. Jack.

200
00:21:24,867 --> 00:21:27,995
"Lmpossible, I know. Not possible...

201
00:21:28,438 --> 00:21:30,429
...but it's happening."

202
00:21:40,818 --> 00:21:42,615
Okay.

203
00:21:46,857 --> 00:21:48,552
Where am I?

204
00:21:53,363 --> 00:21:55,490
Very clever.

205
00:21:57,501 --> 00:21:59,526
"The lake house."

206
00:21:59,970 --> 00:22:02,963
The lake house. As you can see,
I, too, am at the lake house...

207
00:22:03,141 --> 00:22:06,304
...but I'm getting tired of these games
so I'm leaving, okay? Bye.

208
00:22:06,478 --> 00:22:07,706
Thank you. Bye.

209
00:22:10,281 --> 00:22:13,478
Maybe we should
introduce ourselves properly.

210
00:22:18,156 --> 00:22:22,024
I'm a doctor,
dedicated to curing the sick.

211
00:22:22,393 --> 00:22:24,088
At least, trying to.

212
00:22:25,231 --> 00:22:27,563
I'm an architect. I like to build.

213
00:22:27,800 --> 00:22:30,598
And while I wouldn't say
my current project is ideal...

214
00:22:30,836 --> 00:22:35,899
...it allows me to be here, in this place,
and that's enough for now.

215
00:22:36,242 --> 00:22:40,201
But tell me something. If you're working
in a hospital in Chicago now...

216
00:22:40,412 --> 00:22:43,347
...where were you before, in my time?

217
00:22:44,116 --> 00:22:45,743
Two years ago, in your time...

218
00:22:45,951 --> 00:22:50,048
...I was working
in internal medicine in Madison.

219
00:22:53,093 --> 00:22:54,390
Tell me about the future.

220
00:22:55,395 --> 00:22:58,125
What's it like in the year 2006?

221
00:22:59,466 --> 00:23:02,196
I'm afraid the world's
pretty much the same.

222
00:23:03,403 --> 00:23:07,396
Of course, we all dress in shiny metal
jump suits and drive flying cars...

223
00:23:07,607 --> 00:23:11,338
...and no one talks anymore
because we can read each other's minds.

224
00:23:11,546 --> 00:23:14,640
But the truth is, man from the past...

225
00:23:14,882 --> 00:23:18,409
...not much has really changed
in 2006.

226
00:23:20,221 --> 00:23:23,918
Speaking of the past, though,
I've been thinking about the paw prints.

227
00:23:24,125 --> 00:23:28,323
-How is that possible?
-Well, I think we have the same dog.

228
00:23:29,096 --> 00:23:31,621
Oh, yeah? What's yours like?

229
00:23:31,866 --> 00:23:35,633
According to the vet,
mine is eight years old in my time...

230
00:23:35,871 --> 00:23:37,862
...six in yours.

231
00:23:38,373 --> 00:23:43,868
She's skinny, has sad eyes, snores,
and sleeps like a person.

232
00:23:44,079 --> 00:23:46,377
I don't know why, but I call her Jack.

233
00:23:46,582 --> 00:23:48,573
Hello, Jack.

234
00:23:51,753 --> 00:23:54,313
It's nice out here.

235
00:23:54,590 --> 00:23:57,822
Let's not go out for dinner.
Let's stay here.

236
00:23:58,027 --> 00:23:59,961
-Hey.
-We have to eat.

237
00:24:00,163 --> 00:24:02,757
What are you doing?
You're supposed to be asleep.

238
00:24:03,132 --> 00:24:04,326
I'll cook.

239
00:24:05,268 --> 00:24:07,395
I thought you didn't like to cook.

240
00:24:08,104 --> 00:24:10,299
No, I don't like to cook.

241
00:24:10,506 --> 00:24:12,531
Is she gonna marry him?

242
00:24:12,709 --> 00:24:16,338
-What do you think?
-I don't know. He's kind of old.

243
00:24:16,512 --> 00:24:19,709
-Where are you going?
-Okay, he's not that old.

244
00:24:20,283 --> 00:24:22,115
My mom's last boyfriend was bald.

245
00:24:22,820 --> 00:24:24,219
He was nice...

246
00:24:24,388 --> 00:24:27,186
...but my mom didn't marry him.
-No?

247
00:24:27,424 --> 00:24:30,291
"There's always something better
coming around the corner."

248
00:24:30,494 --> 00:24:32,860
That's what she says.

249
00:24:33,297 --> 00:24:36,858
Maybe that's what that lady should do.
Wait for something better...

250
00:24:37,067 --> 00:24:40,036
...to come around the corner.
-Maybe.

251
00:24:42,039 --> 00:24:45,806
But if she's not careful,
she could spend her whole life waiting.

252
00:24:46,745 --> 00:24:49,077
Do you want me to bring
anything back with me?

253
00:24:49,247 --> 00:24:51,875
Yes. What about
a nice bottle of wine...

254
00:24:52,651 --> 00:24:54,209
...to celebrate?

255
00:24:54,452 --> 00:24:57,478
-What time shall I come back?
-Seven o'clock.

256
00:24:57,689 --> 00:25:00,453
Sorry I haven't made it
to the mailbox lately.

257
00:25:00,659 --> 00:25:04,595
It's been a long week. All night shifts.

258
00:25:04,863 --> 00:25:07,958
Good to hear from you.
I thought you left me.

259
00:25:08,167 --> 00:25:11,898
You should know that you're
my only connection to the future.

260
00:25:12,538 --> 00:25:15,769
How come we never talk
about the things we like?

261
00:25:16,108 --> 00:25:19,600
Well, let's see.
Reading the classics to Jack.

262
00:25:19,845 --> 00:25:22,973
-Who's his favorite?
-Dostoyevsky.

263
00:25:23,182 --> 00:25:26,845
For me, this city,
on a day when the light is so clear...

264
00:25:27,053 --> 00:25:28,680
...that I can touch every detail...

265
00:25:28,888 --> 00:25:31,551
...every brick and window
in the buildings I love.

266
00:25:31,758 --> 00:25:36,354
Come on, take a walk with me
this Saturday. Let me show you.

267
00:25:36,563 --> 00:25:39,999
You're crazy. Why are you going
through all this trouble for me?

268
00:25:40,200 --> 00:25:43,226
No trouble. Summer's here.

269
00:25:55,883 --> 00:25:59,546
Okay, your turn. Favorite things.

270
00:25:59,754 --> 00:26:02,587
Where to start? Okay.

271
00:26:02,790 --> 00:26:05,884
When I smell the flowers
before I see them.

272
00:26:06,094 --> 00:26:10,394
When it starts to rain
just as the picnic is ending.

273
00:26:10,598 --> 00:26:14,466
And I love the smell of Jack's paws.

274
00:26:14,669 --> 00:26:17,298
You didn't forget
to mention your husband, did you?

275
00:26:18,240 --> 00:26:21,767
Well, of course I love my husband,
who is also a doctor.

276
00:26:21,977 --> 00:26:24,411
Plastic surgeon
for small farm animals.

277
00:26:24,613 --> 00:26:26,911
Good. I'm married too.

278
00:26:27,116 --> 00:26:30,574
I've got eight children,
and none of them look like me.

279
00:26:30,786 --> 00:26:33,949
-I'm worried, Kate.
-I would be too.

280
00:26:34,356 --> 00:26:35,755
I'm single.

281
00:26:36,592 --> 00:26:38,355
Me too.

282
00:26:41,431 --> 00:26:43,262
Number 27.

283
00:26:43,466 --> 00:26:45,627
She's a beauty.
My father used to tell me...

284
00:26:45,835 --> 00:26:48,702
...she was the grandma
for all the houses in the city.

285
00:26:48,938 --> 00:26:52,374
He used to take me on walks
like I'm taking you now.

286
00:26:52,809 --> 00:26:56,074
-Alex?
-Kate?

287
00:26:56,279 --> 00:26:59,112
I wish we could have
done this walk together.

288
00:27:14,198 --> 00:27:15,995
So, what do you think?

289
00:27:16,300 --> 00:27:18,734
He sounds like a nice boy.

290
00:27:18,903 --> 00:27:21,599
Sounds like a nice boy.
Anything else?

291
00:27:21,806 --> 00:27:25,139
-He has wonderful penmanship.
-Mother...

292
00:27:25,309 --> 00:27:27,710
...look at the date on the letter.
The date.

293
00:27:27,913 --> 00:27:29,403
-You mean the time thing?
-Yes.

294
00:27:29,648 --> 00:27:32,242
-That's just a detail.
-Just a detail?

295
00:27:41,326 --> 00:27:44,420
About the...
The other day...

296
00:27:44,663 --> 00:27:49,533
...it was not a good moment.
I was in a hell of a hurry.

297
00:27:49,869 --> 00:27:51,496
Of course.

298
00:27:52,905 --> 00:27:55,066
You've got some nice pieces here.

299
00:27:55,274 --> 00:27:59,074
Oh, yeah. Music's fine, music helps.

300
00:27:59,779 --> 00:28:01,440
It's like Nietzsche says:

301
00:28:01,681 --> 00:28:04,946
-"Life would be senseless..."
-"Without music."

302
00:28:05,852 --> 00:28:07,752
I guess I told you that, huh?

303
00:28:07,954 --> 00:28:09,387
Pour yourself a drink.

304
00:28:09,589 --> 00:28:12,855
Can you appreciate
a good wine by now?

305
00:28:13,060 --> 00:28:14,960
You bet.

306
00:28:15,796 --> 00:28:18,890
You know, you'll have to forgive
your father for being curious...

307
00:28:19,099 --> 00:28:22,262
...but where have you been
all these years?

308
00:28:22,603 --> 00:28:25,868
I thought your Kerouac days
were behind you.

309
00:28:26,874 --> 00:28:29,672
-I'm sorry, what?
-What?

310
00:28:30,911 --> 00:28:33,402
Oh, you can come up, if you like.

311
00:28:42,123 --> 00:28:43,750
What are you working on?

312
00:28:43,925 --> 00:28:46,985
Oh, I'm just...
I'm just remembering things.

313
00:28:47,228 --> 00:28:49,890
It's not such an easy job,
let me tell you.

314
00:28:50,098 --> 00:28:53,067
Nor is it particularly innocent,
in my case.

315
00:28:53,268 --> 00:28:56,635
Your father is writing his memoirs.

316
00:28:58,339 --> 00:29:00,001
-Are we in it?
-What do you think?

317
00:29:00,175 --> 00:29:01,938
Do you wanna be?

318
00:29:03,078 --> 00:29:04,477
Do you?

319
00:29:04,713 --> 00:29:08,308
Of course.
You were all a part of your father's life.

320
00:29:09,585 --> 00:29:11,678
Why are you talking to me
in the third person?

321
00:29:11,854 --> 00:29:13,515
Well, l... I don't...

322
00:29:13,756 --> 00:29:17,089
Because I'm writing about myself,
I suppose. Why, doesn't it suit you?

323
00:29:19,962 --> 00:29:23,455
I thought you might like these.

324
00:29:25,368 --> 00:29:27,666
What are these?
Something you've been working on?

325
00:29:27,871 --> 00:29:30,738
No, they're... They're yours.

326
00:29:30,941 --> 00:29:35,002
From a house I just bought
on the lake.

327
00:29:36,046 --> 00:29:39,777
Oh, yes, I heard. They said
some sleazy little condo developer...

328
00:29:39,983 --> 00:29:41,974
...had snapped it up.

329
00:29:42,352 --> 00:29:45,618
Oh, come on. Indulge your father.

330
00:29:45,823 --> 00:29:48,815
Can't you take a little joke,
for God's sake?

331
00:29:49,160 --> 00:29:50,957
Come on.

332
00:29:51,128 --> 00:29:52,857
Tell me.

333
00:29:53,331 --> 00:29:55,526
Where have you been?
I really want to know.

334
00:29:55,766 --> 00:29:58,257
I was trying to forget you.

335
00:30:00,004 --> 00:30:02,336
Or forgive you.

336
00:30:03,674 --> 00:30:05,835
Did you succeed?

337
00:30:08,146 --> 00:30:09,841
No.

338
00:30:14,186 --> 00:30:17,212
Let me know
if you need any help remembering.

339
00:30:19,224 --> 00:30:22,284
Oh, yeah, I will.

340
00:30:23,061 --> 00:30:26,690
Charging 360. Get 1 milligram of epi.
Have 300 amio ready in case we need it.

341
00:30:26,898 --> 00:30:29,526
-All clear?
-Clear.

342
00:30:31,704 --> 00:30:33,797
Hold compression, start bagging.

343
00:30:34,007 --> 00:30:35,304
He's got a rhythm. Slow.

344
00:30:35,508 --> 00:30:38,102
-Do we have a pulse with that?
-We got a pulse, thready.

345
00:30:38,344 --> 00:30:40,244
-It's getting stronger.
-Long days, these days.

346
00:30:40,446 --> 00:30:43,176
I just worked 30 hours straight.

347
00:30:43,383 --> 00:30:45,874
Every time I stop to take a breath...

348
00:30:46,085 --> 00:30:49,350
...I realize how isolated
I've let myself become.

349
00:30:49,522 --> 00:30:54,460
Believe me,
you can get a bit desperate.

350
00:30:56,096 --> 00:30:58,564
That one? Okay. There you go.

351
00:30:58,766 --> 00:31:02,964
Nice move. Very nice. Nice.

352
00:31:05,606 --> 00:31:08,632
It's not that I'm complaining,
I love my work.

353
00:31:08,876 --> 00:31:13,210
And our tour through Chicago
opened my eyes to its beauty.

354
00:31:13,414 --> 00:31:16,349
But my heart still misses
the lake house...

355
00:31:16,550 --> 00:31:18,746
...and its trees.

356
00:31:19,654 --> 00:31:22,282
I miss those trees so much.

357
00:32:39,537 --> 00:32:43,064
Don't worry, Kate.
We'll be together in time.

358
00:32:43,307 --> 00:32:46,640
Even if we're far apart,
I'll find a way to be close to you...

359
00:32:46,844 --> 00:32:48,869
...and take care of you.

360
00:32:54,253 --> 00:32:56,050
Katerina.

361
00:32:57,489 --> 00:32:59,252
Take this.

362
00:32:59,725 --> 00:33:02,592
-You should eat more. You too skinny.
-I'm not too skinny.

363
00:33:02,761 --> 00:33:06,026
Remember how you used to eat
when you were little?

364
00:33:06,231 --> 00:33:07,960
-With your hands.
-Yes, I remember.

365
00:33:08,167 --> 00:33:11,000
Now, did you or did you not
write to each other?

366
00:33:11,370 --> 00:33:13,270
-To your father?
-No, to Clark Gable.

367
00:33:13,506 --> 00:33:16,100
Yes, to Dad.

368
00:33:18,545 --> 00:33:20,274
I...

369
00:33:22,715 --> 00:33:24,239
What, Mom?

370
00:33:24,484 --> 00:33:26,475
Before your father...

371
00:33:26,686 --> 00:33:28,415
Yeah?

372
00:33:29,289 --> 00:33:33,487
-There was this boy.

373
00:33:35,428 --> 00:33:36,896
Did you love him?

374
00:33:37,731 --> 00:33:39,460
Yeah.

375
00:33:44,805 --> 00:33:47,399
Well, why didn't you marry him?

376
00:33:48,776 --> 00:33:52,610
So that you could ask me
this question someday.

377
00:34:02,757 --> 00:34:04,816
Looks smaller.

378
00:34:06,795 --> 00:34:09,025
When did he complete it?

379
00:34:10,065 --> 00:34:12,625
You weren't born yet,
and I was 8.

380
00:34:17,339 --> 00:34:20,399
Corbusier meets Frank Lloyd Wright.

381
00:34:21,109 --> 00:34:24,102
You know, Dad played cards
with both of them.

382
00:34:25,181 --> 00:34:28,639
-Sharing a joint.
-Yeah, well...

383
00:34:29,252 --> 00:34:31,186
Can't swim.

384
00:34:31,554 --> 00:34:35,251
There should be a stairway
down to the water, a porch, a deck.

385
00:34:35,825 --> 00:34:38,293
Here, you're in a...
In a box.

386
00:34:38,494 --> 00:34:41,759
A glass box with a view
to everything that's around you...

387
00:34:41,964 --> 00:34:43,431
...but you can't touch it.

388
00:34:43,633 --> 00:34:47,968
No interconnection
between you and what you're looking at.

389
00:34:48,171 --> 00:34:51,004
I don't know, you know.
He's got this big maple growing...

390
00:34:51,208 --> 00:34:54,200
...right in the middle of the house.
-Containment.

391
00:34:57,614 --> 00:35:01,277
Containment and control.

392
00:35:03,086 --> 00:35:07,113
This house is about ownership,
not connection.

393
00:35:07,724 --> 00:35:11,525
I mean, it's beautiful. Seductive, even.

394
00:35:11,729 --> 00:35:14,698
But it's incomplete.

395
00:35:17,001 --> 00:35:18,832
It was all about him.

396
00:35:20,505 --> 00:35:22,905
Dad knew how to build a house,
not a home.

397
00:35:23,908 --> 00:35:25,239
But you know...

398
00:35:25,977 --> 00:35:28,411
...I think he wants us to do
what he couldn't.

399
00:35:29,113 --> 00:35:31,206
But admitting that...

400
00:35:31,916 --> 00:35:35,978
...would mean admitting
that he came up short in some way...

401
00:35:36,188 --> 00:35:38,053
...that he could do more.

402
00:35:38,257 --> 00:35:40,316
And that tortures him.

403
00:35:41,660 --> 00:35:44,151
Do you remember
being here with Mom?

404
00:35:51,003 --> 00:35:53,062
I remember she tried
to make it work here...

405
00:35:54,340 --> 00:35:56,206
...with us...

406
00:35:56,843 --> 00:35:58,435
...with him.

407
00:36:00,580 --> 00:36:02,241
Hey, what about Visionary Vanguard?

408
00:36:02,415 --> 00:36:05,043
-What about it?
-Come on.

409
00:36:05,218 --> 00:36:09,086
You can't convince me you're gonna
be happy building saltboxes for tourists.

410
00:36:09,589 --> 00:36:11,853
Nobody's gonna admire you for that.

411
00:36:12,058 --> 00:36:15,118
-Admire me for that?
-Yeah, Visionary Vanguard.

412
00:36:15,895 --> 00:36:17,886
That's your idea.

413
00:36:18,098 --> 00:36:19,930
I can't. But you can keep the name.

414
00:36:20,101 --> 00:36:22,262
No, come on.
It's gotta be you and me.

415
00:36:22,470 --> 00:36:25,234
Henry, I'm sorry, I can't.

416
00:36:25,439 --> 00:36:26,929
I just...

417
00:36:27,174 --> 00:36:30,371
-What?
-I've got other plans.

418
00:36:30,544 --> 00:36:32,569
You have a girlfriend?

419
00:36:34,415 --> 00:36:35,473
No...

420
00:36:35,649 --> 00:36:37,412
No.

421
00:36:37,785 --> 00:36:40,913
-What is that? You hesitated.
-No, I didn't hesitate.

422
00:36:42,724 --> 00:36:45,124
Come on, man.
I don't have any time for that.

423
00:36:46,628 --> 00:36:48,687
What does time have to do with it?

424
00:36:49,464 --> 00:36:51,830
Oh, you're gonna think I'm crazy.

425
00:36:56,772 --> 00:36:59,206
My dearest Mr. Wyler:

426
00:36:59,408 --> 00:37:02,138
Are you willing to play a game
with me?

427
00:37:02,778 --> 00:37:06,010
Two years ago today,
I was taking the 145 train to Madison...

428
00:37:06,249 --> 00:37:09,616
...from the Riverside station
and I forgot something there.

429
00:37:09,819 --> 00:37:12,344
It was a gift from my father.

430
00:37:12,822 --> 00:37:16,815
If you find it,
can you please put it in the mailbox?

431
00:37:17,827 --> 00:37:19,954
It would mean a lot.

432
00:37:20,263 --> 00:37:23,494
Yours, Kate.

433
00:37:39,249 --> 00:37:44,243
-Final call for the 5:46 to Madison.
-Do you really wanna know? Come on.

434
00:37:44,455 --> 00:37:46,650
-All aboard.
-Okay.

435
00:37:56,768 --> 00:37:58,360
I'll call you.

436
00:38:39,679 --> 00:38:43,046
Kate, I found it. I have it with me.

437
00:38:43,250 --> 00:38:45,946
One day I'll get it to you. Trust me.

438
00:38:46,186 --> 00:38:49,178
I know how important it is to you.

439
00:38:50,457 --> 00:38:53,893
You might not remember,
but we saw each other.

440
00:38:54,094 --> 00:38:56,187
At least, I saw you.

441
00:38:57,430 --> 00:39:01,595
You never told me
how beautiful you are.

442
00:39:01,836 --> 00:39:04,327
Well, maybe you saw somebody else.

443
00:39:04,539 --> 00:39:07,030
That was a bad hair year for me.

444
00:39:07,241 --> 00:39:10,574
Long brown hair.
Gentle, unguarded eyes.

445
00:39:10,778 --> 00:39:12,643
Okay, okay, okay.

446
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:14,711
You saw me.

447
00:39:15,383 --> 00:39:17,544
But I still don't know
what you look like.

448
00:39:19,120 --> 00:39:22,578
Well, why don't we just get together
in the future...

449
00:39:22,790 --> 00:39:25,453
...and you can let me know
what you think.

450
00:39:26,428 --> 00:39:28,225
It's a date.

451
00:39:31,433 --> 00:39:32,923
Okay.

452
00:39:33,135 --> 00:39:37,469
Why don't you call me
July 10th, 2006...

453
00:39:37,673 --> 00:39:42,906
...at 9:05 p.m.

454
00:39:57,594 --> 00:39:59,960
-Hello.
-Kate?

455
00:40:00,163 --> 00:40:02,996
-Yes.
-It's Morgan.

456
00:40:05,902 --> 00:40:07,494
Morgan.

457
00:40:07,704 --> 00:40:10,606
I'm in Chicago. I came for a meeting,
but it was canceled...

458
00:40:10,808 --> 00:40:12,537
...so I thought I'd give you a call.

459
00:40:13,344 --> 00:40:15,471
Hey, have you eaten?

460
00:40:15,679 --> 00:40:19,171
-No, but I'm not...
-Neither have I. I realized I'm starving.

461
00:40:19,416 --> 00:40:21,976
-We could grab a quick bite.
-Okay.

462
00:40:22,186 --> 00:40:24,051
-Yeah?
-All right.

463
00:40:24,288 --> 00:40:27,917
-Hey, wait up.
-Watch out, man.

464
00:40:28,225 --> 00:40:30,989
-All right.
-Looks pretty good.

465
00:40:31,195 --> 00:40:32,662
-Perfect.
-No, Morgan, it's...

466
00:40:32,863 --> 00:40:34,195
-It's not.
-No, no, trust me.

467
00:40:34,432 --> 00:40:36,900
It's... Okay.

468
00:40:38,370 --> 00:40:39,632
Hi there.

469
00:40:39,838 --> 00:40:41,999
One sec.
Could you hold on for a moment?

470
00:40:42,173 --> 00:40:44,573
-We'd love a table for two.
-The name?

471
00:40:46,444 --> 00:40:48,309
We don't...
We don't have a reservation.

472
00:40:48,480 --> 00:40:51,415
I'm sorry, sir,
we're booked until October.

473
00:40:52,550 --> 00:40:53,642
October?

474
00:40:56,021 --> 00:40:57,751
Well...

475
00:40:58,391 --> 00:41:00,552
...l'll get back to you.

476
00:41:02,995 --> 00:41:04,860
That went well.

477
00:41:05,064 --> 00:41:07,328
It's no big deal.

478
00:41:11,337 --> 00:41:12,736
Oh, come on, stop it.

479
00:41:12,905 --> 00:41:15,840
It's the best restaurant in town.
Nobody gets a table here.

480
00:41:16,042 --> 00:41:19,569
-No, it's not that.
-Well, what is it?

481
00:41:23,083 --> 00:41:25,176
I didn't do this right.

482
00:41:26,219 --> 00:41:29,211
-There wasn't a meeting.
-You'd see me if there was no big deal.

483
00:41:29,423 --> 00:41:30,515
-Lf it was just...
-Ambush.

484
00:41:30,724 --> 00:41:33,557
-You know, coffee,
and coffee can turn into dinner...

485
00:41:33,727 --> 00:41:36,218
...dinner can turn into...
-Turn into what?

486
00:41:36,396 --> 00:41:38,626
I do sometimes
get a few steps ahead of myself.

487
00:41:38,865 --> 00:41:43,929
Morgan, a few steps?
You're always leaping 10 steps ahead.

488
00:41:45,740 --> 00:41:47,230
We were dating, what, a week?

489
00:41:47,442 --> 00:41:50,377
And you had our entire future
mapped out for us?

490
00:41:51,145 --> 00:41:54,637
In my residency, you were picking out
real estate. I'd go to your house...

491
00:41:54,882 --> 00:41:58,147
...you'd have the entire town
in your house to meet me.

492
00:41:58,386 --> 00:42:02,220
