747
01:00:51,923 --> 01:00:54,721
-Mr. Wyler, the architect?
-Yes.

748
01:00:54,926 --> 01:00:58,054
I'm Anna Klyczynski.
I'm the Attending for your father.

749
01:00:58,262 --> 01:01:00,423
Hey. What happened? How is he?

750
01:01:00,632 --> 01:01:05,126
He's okay. He's had a heart attack.
Fortunately, relatively minor.

751
01:01:05,370 --> 01:01:08,533
His vitals are fine and he's stable...

752
01:01:08,707 --> 01:01:10,800
...but it will require an intervention.

753
01:01:11,043 --> 01:01:14,069
He's agreed to schedule it
for tomorrow.

754
01:01:29,095 --> 01:01:31,791
Good to see you're taking it easy.

755
01:01:32,599 --> 01:01:36,660
Well, you... You didn't need to come.
I'm perfectly well.

756
01:01:37,036 --> 01:01:39,095
Perfectly all right.

757
01:01:39,305 --> 01:01:41,739
Well, you had a heart attack, Dad.

758
01:01:41,941 --> 01:01:45,274
I had an episode, for chrissake.

759
01:01:45,478 --> 01:01:47,413
Nothing more.

760
01:01:48,115 --> 01:01:51,448
Appreciate it if you kept everything
in its perspective.

761
01:01:53,654 --> 01:01:57,055
Well then, I just wanna let you know
I'm here if you need anything.

762
01:01:59,193 --> 01:02:00,990
Coffee.

763
01:02:01,428 --> 01:02:03,123
What?

764
01:02:03,564 --> 01:02:05,361
You heard me.

765
01:02:07,768 --> 01:02:09,599
Coffee.

766
01:02:11,439 --> 01:02:13,669
There's something
I never told you, Kate.

767
01:02:13,875 --> 01:02:16,343
You see, it was my father
who built the lake house.

768
01:02:16,578 --> 01:02:19,604
I mean, with his own hands.

769
01:02:19,815 --> 01:02:22,648
And it was a long time ago,
before he was famous...

770
01:02:22,851 --> 01:02:26,082
...when he still had a family
and worshipped my mother.

771
01:02:26,288 --> 01:02:30,088
Her name was Mary,
and the house was a gift for her.

772
01:02:30,292 --> 01:02:33,126
She was smart and funny.

773
01:02:33,329 --> 01:02:36,992
She could have done anything, but chose
to take care of my brother and I...

774
01:02:37,200 --> 01:02:38,997
...and help him build his career.

775
01:02:39,202 --> 01:02:43,229
You see, the more successful he became,
the more impossible he was to live with.

776
01:02:43,472 --> 01:02:47,033
Finally, she just couldn't take
living with him anymore.

777
01:02:47,243 --> 01:02:50,178
She left him.

778
01:02:50,379 --> 01:02:52,506
Within a year, she got sick.

779
01:02:52,715 --> 01:02:56,379
Unfortunately, she never learned
how to stop loving him.

780
01:02:57,621 --> 01:03:00,021
He wasn't at the funeral.

781
01:03:01,358 --> 01:03:03,622
When I asked him why...

782
01:03:09,366 --> 01:03:12,164
Go on, Alex. What did he say?

783
01:03:16,139 --> 01:03:19,871
He said, "She was dead to me the
moment she stepped out of the house."

784
01:03:22,881 --> 01:03:27,181
And then he gave me
one of his architect-of-the-year grins.

785
01:03:42,200 --> 01:03:43,463
I hope you appreciate this.

786
01:03:43,702 --> 01:03:46,432
I had to sneak past
three nurses and your Attending.

787
01:03:46,672 --> 01:03:48,970
Oh, jeez, it's hot.

788
01:03:49,308 --> 01:03:50,707
It's not decaf, is it?

789
01:03:50,910 --> 01:03:52,775
It should be, but it isn't.

790
01:03:56,482 --> 01:03:59,110
That's not bad. Thank you...

791
01:03:59,318 --> 01:04:00,945
...son.

792
01:04:01,186 --> 01:04:04,280
-You're welcome.
-Where's your brother?

793
01:04:04,456 --> 01:04:06,584
I sent him away.
He wasn't feeling well.

794
01:04:06,793 --> 01:04:09,694
-You know how he is, he worries.
-Yeah, I know.

795
01:04:09,896 --> 01:04:11,989
He gets that from your mother,
I'm afraid.

796
01:04:12,766 --> 01:04:14,233
She always worried too much.

797
01:04:14,434 --> 01:04:16,129
What are you looking at?

798
01:04:16,937 --> 01:04:18,734
Oh, yeah, here, take a gander.

799
01:04:18,939 --> 01:04:22,306
It's a proposal for a museum.

800
01:04:22,509 --> 01:04:25,706
-Who is it?
-Someone new.

801
01:04:26,613 --> 01:04:29,913
Oh, I like the walkways,
where the light falls.

802
01:04:30,117 --> 01:04:31,744
What are the materials?

803
01:04:32,153 --> 01:04:34,144
Granite. Aluminum.

804
01:04:34,355 --> 01:04:36,823
White panels
are straight out of Meier...

805
01:04:37,024 --> 01:04:41,358
...but the interior color coming through
the front windows, that's different.

806
01:04:42,196 --> 01:04:45,529
It's not new,
but it's clean, uncluttered.

807
01:04:45,766 --> 01:04:47,461
I like it.

808
01:04:48,035 --> 01:04:51,095
When was the last time
you were in Barcelona?

809
01:04:52,874 --> 01:04:55,342
Years ago, with you, Mom and Henry.

810
01:04:55,544 --> 01:04:58,172
Do you remember visiting
Casa de la Caritat?

811
01:04:59,348 --> 01:05:00,975
The almshouse.

812
01:05:01,183 --> 01:05:03,651
That's right. You mentioned Meier.

813
01:05:03,852 --> 01:05:08,755
His Barcelona museum stands
in the same area as Casa de la Caritat.

814
01:05:08,957 --> 01:05:10,948
It drinks the same light.

815
01:05:11,159 --> 01:05:16,063
Meier designed a series of louvered
skylights to capture that light...

816
01:05:16,299 --> 01:05:21,066
...and cast it inward to illuminate
the art within, but indirectly.

817
01:05:21,304 --> 01:05:26,298
And that was important,
because although light enhances art...

818
01:05:26,509 --> 01:05:31,310
...it can also degrade it. But you know
all that already, you son of a gun.

819
01:05:31,481 --> 01:05:33,381
Now, this...

820
01:05:35,318 --> 01:05:37,343
...where do you suppose
this is to be built?

821
01:05:37,520 --> 01:05:38,579
I have no idea.

822
01:05:38,756 --> 01:05:41,190
-Oh, but you said you liked it.
-Conceptually.

823
01:05:41,358 --> 01:05:43,588
Now, come on.

824
01:05:43,827 --> 01:05:46,489
You know as well as I do
that the light in Barcelona...

825
01:05:46,697 --> 01:05:49,063
...is quite different
from the light in Tokyo.

826
01:05:49,233 --> 01:05:52,327
And the light in Tokyo
is different from that in Prague.

827
01:05:52,536 --> 01:05:58,532
A truly great structure, one that
is meant to stand the tests of time...

828
01:05:58,742 --> 01:06:01,233
...never disregards its environment.

829
01:06:01,445 --> 01:06:03,243
An architect takes that into account.

830
01:06:03,448 --> 01:06:08,181
He knows that if he wants presence,
he must consult with nature.

831
01:06:08,386 --> 01:06:12,789
He must be captivated by the light.

832
01:06:12,957 --> 01:06:16,688
Always the light. Always.

833
01:07:12,286 --> 01:07:14,584
Hey. I have an emergency.
Take my shift. Please.

834
01:07:19,594 --> 01:07:21,118
Hello.

835
01:07:21,329 --> 01:07:23,957
-Mr. Wyler?
-Yes.

836
01:07:24,165 --> 01:07:27,362
This is Dr. Klyczynski
at Chicago City Hospital.

837
01:07:28,102 --> 01:07:31,594
I'm afraid I have some
difficult news for you.

838
01:07:34,409 --> 01:07:36,969
I'm so sorry, Alex.

839
01:07:38,213 --> 01:07:41,307
I wish somehow
I could be there with you...

840
01:07:41,850 --> 01:07:45,547
...that we could sit together and look
out over the water and the light...

841
01:07:45,787 --> 01:07:48,688
...in this house your father built.

842
01:07:51,693 --> 01:07:54,560
I could be a shoulder for you
like you've been for me.

843
01:07:54,796 --> 01:07:57,925
And tell you that
everything is gonna be okay.

844
01:07:59,836 --> 01:08:02,669
If I could do one thing for you today...

845
01:08:02,872 --> 01:08:04,931
...from here...

846
01:08:05,141 --> 01:08:08,736
...one small, simple thing
from the future...

847
01:08:09,345 --> 01:08:11,336
...I hope this is it.

848
01:08:12,749 --> 01:08:15,479
It won't be published
for a couple of years...

849
01:08:15,685 --> 01:08:18,347
...but I don't think
you should have to wait that long.

850
01:08:20,056 --> 01:08:23,026
I hope it helps you know
how much you were loved.

851
01:10:07,468 --> 01:10:09,868
Pick a place. I'll be there, I promise.

852
01:10:10,104 --> 01:10:11,435
Tomorrow, what do you say?

853
01:10:11,639 --> 01:10:13,470
But, Alex,
it won't be tomorrow for you.

854
01:10:13,675 --> 01:10:17,077
-You're gonna have to wait two years.
-I know, I don't care. I'll wait.

855
01:10:17,279 --> 01:10:18,610
Are you sure? I don't know.

856
01:10:18,814 --> 01:10:21,282
I do. I've never been so sure
of anything in my life.

857
01:10:21,483 --> 01:10:24,611
Okay. I'll see you in two years, then.

858
01:10:24,820 --> 01:10:27,084
See you tomorrow, then.

859
01:10:27,489 --> 01:10:29,184
Kate...

860
01:10:29,391 --> 01:10:31,382
...where would you like to go?

861
01:10:34,196 --> 01:10:35,857
II Mare.

862
01:10:36,031 --> 01:10:38,022
When were you hoping
to dine with us?

863
01:10:38,233 --> 01:10:39,826
Two years from tomorrow.

864
01:10:40,036 --> 01:10:42,197
-Two years from tomorrow?
-Yeah.

865
01:10:42,405 --> 01:10:44,373
-Two years?
-From tomorrow.

866
01:10:46,343 --> 01:10:48,334
-Hi.
-Hello. Name?

867
01:10:48,511 --> 01:10:49,637
Forster.

868
01:10:49,813 --> 01:10:51,178
-Can I have your name?
-Wyler.

869
01:10:51,348 --> 01:10:53,908
Or Wyler, I'm...
I'm really not sure.

870
01:10:54,084 --> 01:10:56,314
I think we should be able
to accommodate you.

871
01:10:56,519 --> 01:10:57,577
-Great.
-Wyler?

872
01:10:59,756 --> 01:11:01,246
Wyler.

873
01:11:02,893 --> 01:11:05,361
Your waiter will be right with you.

874
01:11:29,521 --> 01:11:31,682
Good evening, miss.

875
01:11:33,358 --> 01:11:35,792
Complimentary.

876
01:11:46,071 --> 01:11:48,905
-Thank you.
-Good luck.

877
01:12:11,564 --> 01:12:13,931
Another glass for the lady?

878
01:13:41,591 --> 01:13:43,684
You weren't there.

879
01:13:44,027 --> 01:13:46,223
You didn't come.

880
01:13:52,603 --> 01:13:54,400
I don't understand.

881
01:13:54,605 --> 01:13:57,733
Something must have happened.
I'm sorry.

882
01:13:57,942 --> 01:14:00,809
I've got two years, Kate.
We can try again.

883
01:14:01,012 --> 01:14:05,244
No, Alex, it's too late.

884
01:14:05,449 --> 01:14:09,045
It already happened. It didn't work.

885
01:14:09,254 --> 01:14:11,188
Don't give up on me, Kate.

886
01:14:11,390 --> 01:14:15,087
What about Persuasion?
You told me. They wait.

887
01:14:15,327 --> 01:14:17,352
They meet again,
they have another chance.

888
01:14:17,563 --> 01:14:19,690
Life is not a book, Alex.

889
01:14:19,898 --> 01:14:22,389
And it can be over in a second.

890
01:14:22,601 --> 01:14:25,968
I was having lunch with my mother
at Daley Plaza...

891
01:14:26,204 --> 01:14:28,934
...and a man was killed
right in front of me.

892
01:14:29,141 --> 01:14:31,372
He died in my arms.

893
01:14:31,578 --> 01:14:33,102
And I thought:

894
01:14:33,346 --> 01:14:37,612
"It can't end just like that
on Valentine's Day."

895
01:14:38,551 --> 01:14:41,543
I thought about all the people
who love him, waiting at home...

896
01:14:41,754 --> 01:14:44,245
...who will never see him again.

897
01:14:45,158 --> 01:14:47,092
And then I thought:

898
01:14:47,293 --> 01:14:49,625
"What if there is no one?"

899
01:14:50,430 --> 01:14:55,926
What if you live your whole life
and no one is waiting?

900
01:14:56,437 --> 01:15:00,373
So I drove to the lake house
looking for any kind of answer.

901
01:15:00,574 --> 01:15:02,974
And I found you.

902
01:15:03,177 --> 01:15:05,611
And I let myself get lost.

903
01:15:05,813 --> 01:15:11,183
Lost in this beautiful fantasy
where time stood still.

904
01:15:11,652 --> 01:15:14,018
But it's not real, Alex.

905
01:15:14,254 --> 01:15:19,192
I have to learn to live
the life that I have got.

906
01:15:20,795 --> 01:15:22,990
Please don't write anymore.

907
01:15:23,198 --> 01:15:25,496
Don't try to find me.

908
01:15:26,434 --> 01:15:29,096
Let me let you go.

909
01:16:16,486 --> 01:16:18,317
Hello.

910
01:16:19,089 --> 01:16:22,024
What? Sorry, hold on.
I can't hear you. I'll be back, sorry.

911
01:16:22,225 --> 01:16:24,887
Hello. Hold on. Hold on.

912
01:16:25,328 --> 01:16:27,024
Hello.

913
01:16:29,567 --> 01:16:31,330
Hi.

914
01:16:36,874 --> 01:16:39,069
How long are you here?

915
01:16:42,280 --> 01:16:45,613
-I'm at a bar with some friends.
-Come.

916
01:16:45,850 --> 01:16:48,410
Well, don't get too excited.

917
01:16:49,855 --> 01:16:52,415
I find that hard to believe.

918
01:16:54,393 --> 01:16:55,860
It is good.

919
01:16:56,061 --> 01:16:59,053
And it was really good
to hear your voice.

920
01:16:59,264 --> 01:17:02,597
I was surprised how good
it was to hear your voice.

921
01:17:05,738 --> 01:17:07,228
So how was your meeting?

922
01:17:07,439 --> 01:17:09,566
-It was good.
-Yeah?

923
01:17:09,775 --> 01:17:12,608
Yeah, l... I got the job.

924
01:17:12,811 --> 01:17:15,144
-Really?
-Yeah.

925
01:17:15,582 --> 01:17:17,743
-Well, congratulations.
-Imagine that.

926
01:17:17,951 --> 01:17:23,583
Yeah. A telecom company.
I'll be in-house counsel. Pays well.

927
01:17:23,790 --> 01:17:25,883
And it's here...

928
01:17:26,092 --> 01:17:27,559
...in Chicago.

929
01:17:28,394 --> 01:17:30,123
Well...

930
01:17:30,330 --> 01:17:32,423
...it's great news.

931
01:17:34,801 --> 01:17:36,599
Hey.

932
01:17:40,574 --> 01:17:42,269
What?

933
01:18:02,464 --> 01:18:03,954
Jack.

934
01:18:04,166 --> 01:18:06,100
Hey, Jack.

935
01:18:06,434 --> 01:18:08,197
Jack.

936
01:19:28,653 --> 01:19:30,917
Are you gonna
come down this weekend?

937
01:19:33,092 --> 01:19:35,287
Don't you miss me a little bit?

938
01:19:35,961 --> 01:19:38,429
Oh, just a little bit. Not a lot, huh?

939
01:19:38,898 --> 01:19:42,561
Okay. No, I heard you. Yeah.

940
01:19:44,436 --> 01:19:47,701
Kate, I'm gonna
have to call you back, okay?

941
01:20:02,555 --> 01:20:04,989
Still wanna rent a lake house?

942
01:20:05,926 --> 01:20:08,258
It's what Kate wants.

943
01:20:08,461 --> 01:20:11,055
How the hell do you know
what Kate wants?

944
01:20:12,432 --> 01:20:14,093
Trust me.

945
01:20:25,980 --> 01:20:29,108
Hey, you. I know you.

946
01:20:35,456 --> 01:20:38,152
Whatever you want out back.

947
01:21:08,057 --> 01:21:09,888
What do you think?

948
01:21:10,493 --> 01:21:12,620
You're fixating. You know?

949
01:21:13,663 --> 01:21:15,494
Why do you keep
tweaking the lake house?

950
01:21:15,698 --> 01:21:17,791
Why don't you do your own work?

951
01:21:17,967 --> 01:21:20,197
Because it's hers.

952
01:21:20,570 --> 01:21:25,837
You're talking about the girl
from the future.

953
01:21:26,042 --> 01:21:27,704
Kate.

954
01:21:28,545 --> 01:21:31,309
And you're still writing with Kate?

955
01:21:31,682 --> 01:21:35,049
-No.
-Why not?

956
01:21:36,520 --> 01:21:38,078
She asked me not to.

957
01:21:38,789 --> 01:21:40,484
Why?

958
01:21:42,793 --> 01:21:44,488
Time.

959
01:21:48,399 --> 01:21:49,923
Hey, come on.

960
01:21:50,167 --> 01:21:53,899
This is a good thing.
You know, you need a real woman.

961
01:21:54,105 --> 01:21:57,199
-A woman...
-Henry, listen.

962
01:21:58,410 --> 01:22:00,207
Listen to me.

963
01:22:00,678 --> 01:22:05,672
While it lasted, she was
more real to me than any of that stuff.

964
01:22:05,884 --> 01:22:10,014
She was more real to me
than anything I've ever known.

965
01:22:12,223 --> 01:22:14,055
I saw her.

966
01:22:14,927 --> 01:22:16,758
I kissed her.

967
01:22:19,131 --> 01:22:20,758
I love her.

968
01:22:23,936 --> 01:22:26,029
And now she's gone.

969
01:22:34,947 --> 01:22:36,710
She's gone.

970
01:22:44,124 --> 01:22:45,751
And Duckett squirts through.

971
01:22:46,259 --> 01:22:47,954
First thing...

972
01:22:49,496 --> 01:22:51,862
How could the Ab Scissor
four-minute ab machine...?

973
01:22:52,065 --> 01:22:54,727
-And your potatoes
cooking on the top.

974
01:22:54,935 --> 01:22:58,496
It's nice out here. Let's stay here.

975
01:22:58,738 --> 01:23:00,604
But we have to eat.

976
01:23:01,609 --> 01:23:04,806
We can eat here. I'll cook.

977
01:23:05,179 --> 01:23:07,443
I thought you didn't like to cook.

978
01:23:08,082 --> 01:23:10,380
No, I don't like to cook.

979
01:23:12,019 --> 01:23:15,318
But I have a chicken in the icebox,
and you're eating it.

980
01:23:15,523 --> 01:23:17,650
What about all
the washing-up afterward?

981
01:23:17,892 --> 01:23:20,452
-We'll eat with our fingers.
-Could you turn that down?

982
01:23:20,661 --> 01:23:22,094
Don't we need any plates?

983
01:23:22,296 --> 01:23:25,994
Yes. One for you,
and one for...

984
01:24:37,609 --> 01:24:41,045
"There could have been
no two hearts so open...

985
01:24:41,713 --> 01:24:44,511
...no tastes so similar...

986
01:24:45,717 --> 01:24:48,618
...no feelings so in unison."

987
01:25:03,202 --> 01:25:08,037
Ten, nine, eight, seven, six...

988
01:25:08,241 --> 01:25:12,735
...five, four, three, two, one.

989
01:25:12,945 --> 01:25:15,812
Happy New Year!

990
01:25:28,395 --> 01:25:30,158
Come in.

991
01:25:45,046 --> 01:25:46,673
Hi.

992
01:25:47,181 --> 01:25:48,671
Hi.

993
01:25:50,184 --> 01:25:51,617
What do you think?

994
01:25:51,819 --> 01:25:53,684
This is what I gave up lunch for?

995
01:25:53,921 --> 01:25:58,654
-I know it needs work.
-Work? How about a wrecking ball?

996
01:25:58,960 --> 01:26:01,986
I found an architect
who specializes in renovations.

997
01:26:02,196 --> 01:26:04,630
I made an appointment for tomorrow.

998
01:26:09,138 --> 01:26:10,696
Ambush.

999
01:26:10,939 --> 01:26:12,201
Come on.

1000
01:26:12,441 --> 01:26:15,933
We can't stay in my apartment.
We've been there over a year.

1001
01:26:17,079 --> 01:26:18,808
I wanna keep moving forward.

1002
01:26:29,392 --> 01:26:32,691
-It's a new firm.
-"New" as in inexperienced?

1003
01:26:32,896 --> 01:26:35,660
No. "New" as in cheap.

1004
01:26:45,875 --> 01:26:48,241
Hi, Dr. Forster.
We'll be with you in a moment.

1005
01:26:48,478 --> 01:26:50,173
Great, thank you.

1006
01:27:03,928 --> 01:27:07,022
Oh, by the way...

1007
01:27:08,432 --> 01:27:10,559
...happy Valentine's Day.

1008
01:27:10,768 --> 01:27:13,896
Oh, God, Katie,
I didn't get you anything.

1009
01:27:14,138 --> 01:27:17,267
I'm sorry. I've just been
so swamped and...

1010
01:27:17,509 --> 01:27:19,409
Doesn't matter.

1011
01:27:35,927 --> 01:27:39,694
-What is this?
-It's global warming.

1012
01:27:41,934 --> 01:27:45,927
Dr. Forster?
Hi, I'm sorry to have kept you waiting.

1013
01:28:04,725 --> 01:28:07,159
-Hi. Good to see you again.
-Dr. Forster. You too.

1014
01:28:07,394 --> 01:28:10,295
-Hi, I'm Morgan.
-Hey, Morgan. Vanessa Vanderbeck.

1015
01:28:10,497 --> 01:28:14,797
So obviously, the first thing you see
is what we had talked about. The atrium.

1016
01:28:15,502 --> 01:28:16,901
That's stunning.

1017
01:28:17,070 --> 01:28:20,597
So we were able to do it with all
the glass panels in the metal structure?

1018
01:28:20,808 --> 01:28:22,400
-Yeah.
-Can l...?

1019
01:28:22,676 --> 01:28:23,973
Wanna get a beer after work?

1020
01:28:24,211 --> 01:28:28,273
I'm sorry, I can't. I'm taking
Vanessa out for Valentine's Day.

1021
01:28:31,986 --> 01:28:33,476
Wait.

1022
01:28:34,022 --> 01:28:35,455
Say that again.

1023
01:28:35,657 --> 01:28:38,785
It's Valentine's Day today.
I'm taking out Vanessa, my girlfriend.

1024
01:28:38,993 --> 01:28:42,360
Cold champagne, some oysters,
maybe a little chocolate.

1025
01:28:42,597 --> 01:28:46,089
-What's the date?
-It's February 14th.

1026
01:28:47,001 --> 01:28:51,268
-February 14th, 2006.
-Yeah.

1027
01:28:51,874 --> 01:28:54,741
-Stunning. Thank you so much.
-Our pleasure.

1028
01:28:54,944 --> 01:28:57,378
Thank you. Henry will
make sure you have everything.

1029
01:28:57,613 --> 01:28:59,513
Great. They were absolutely beautiful.

1030
01:28:59,748 --> 01:29:01,238
Thank you.

1031
01:29:02,518 --> 01:29:04,008
What?

1032
01:29:05,488 --> 01:29:08,787
Katie, I gotta get back to work.

1033
01:29:11,761 --> 01:29:13,626
Who did this drawing?

1034
01:29:13,830 --> 01:29:15,957
My brother did, actually.

1035
01:29:16,132 --> 01:29:17,497
Who's your brother?

1036
01:29:17,701 --> 01:29:19,692
Alex Wyler.

1037
01:29:20,003 --> 01:29:21,766
Did you know him?

1038
01:29:23,907 --> 01:29:25,465
Yeah.

1039
01:29:26,409 --> 01:29:28,172
Yeah, I know him.

1040
01:29:30,680 --> 01:29:32,875
Do you know how
I can get in touch with him?

1041
01:29:33,083 --> 01:29:35,985
Is he...?
Is he anywhere that I can...?

1042
01:29:38,689 --> 01:29:40,554
I'm sorry.

1043
01:29:41,192 --> 01:29:45,219
He died...

1044
01:29:45,696 --> 01:29:48,392
...two years ago today, actually.

1045
01:29:51,702 --> 01:29:53,795
There was an accident.

1046
01:30:11,456 --> 01:30:13,048
Where?

1047
01:30:16,728 --> 01:30:18,218
Kate.

1048
01:30:20,600 --> 01:30:23,034
Wait, just stop. Just stop.

1049
01:30:23,536 --> 01:30:25,629
Goddamn it, answer me.

1050
01:30:25,939 --> 01:30:29,966
What is the matter? Kate.

1051
01:30:32,645 --> 01:30:34,203
Kate!

1052
01:31:38,648 --> 01:31:41,674
Sixty degrees on Valentine's Day.

1053
01:31:41,917 --> 01:31:44,215
This cannot be Chicago.

1054
01:31:44,620 --> 01:31:47,646
The TV says it's global warming.

1055
01:31:48,024 --> 01:31:49,787
Nothing wrong with that.

1056
01:31:49,992 --> 01:31:51,721
It's a dangerous thing.

1057
01:31:52,161 --> 01:31:53,857
Alex...

1058
01:31:55,298 --> 01:31:58,199
...I know why you
didn't show up that night.

1059
01:31:58,435 --> 01:32:01,700
It was you at Daley Plaza that day.

1060
01:32:02,873 --> 01:32:04,670
It was you.

1061
01:32:05,575 --> 01:32:07,634
Please, don't go.

1062
01:32:08,712 --> 01:32:12,170
Just wait. Please.

1063
01:32:13,150 --> 01:32:14,515
Don't look for me.

1064
01:32:14,718 --> 01:32:17,051
Don't try to find me.

1065
01:32:19,223 --> 01:32:21,088
I love you.

1066
01:32:23,928 --> 01:32:27,557
And it's taken me all this time
to say it, but I love you.

1067
01:32:35,073 --> 01:32:36,700
And if you still care for me...

1068
01:32:38,576 --> 01:32:40,511
...wait for me.

1069
01:32:41,046 --> 01:32:43,037
Wait with me.

1070
01:32:43,248 --> 01:32:46,740
Just wait. Wait.

1071
01:32:55,494 --> 01:32:57,894
Wait two years, Alex.

1072
01:32:58,363 --> 01:33:00,695
Come to the lake house.

1073
01:33:01,066 --> 01:33:02,898
I'm here.

1074
01:34:00,095 --> 01:34:01,926
You waited.